I don't like the way he chose to handle that request for a SoW, but that doesn't make him a bad guy in any way.  For those who wonder where I did that, it's in the tenth post of this thread most people apparently politely ignored ;-)  Anyway, sorry for being harsh on you Lasgalen.<br>
<br>
I'm new.<br>
I played a total of six weeks.  Two characters.  I'm not a beggar.  I try to role-play my requests for SoW and I often offer to pay.  I never had to so far though, most people just seem thrilled to be offered some coins for a SoW they usually end up giving my full buffs I don't need because I'm just gonna be running from Everfrost to Freeport anyway.  That's very nice of them and I usually thanked them until they get sick of it.<br>
<br>
In a few weeks, I will either become a role-player or a dood (however you spell it).  It depends mostly on who I will spend my gaming time with.  Some role-players treated me like a twit because I didn't type OOC before making out of character statements or used emotes to get a message across (I only spoke gnomish back then). I ended up spending more time in the company of powergamers and other kinds of non-role-players.  I'm not masochistic.  I don't enjoy the company of people who are rude to me.<br>
<br>
I'm sure I'm not the only newcomer like this.  Some probably are doods and beggars who expect to be greeted with gifts of hundred of PPs.  But others are just clueless.  If the role-players want the clueless ones to become role-players, they will have to take the time to give them a clue.  And I know that sucks, but I think it takes more time to teach someone how to role-play than powerplay, so role-players probably have to invest more time and energy in newcomers if they want to keep the balance in their favor.  Anyway.  I don't know if this makes sense to anyone.  I hope it does, because that's basically all I had to say.<br>
<br>
I wish you all happy hunting.<br>
<br>
Soyin,<br>
Some gnome.<br>
